'''May Mills [[OBE]]''' (19 July 1890 – 26 January 1984)  was a pioneering sports administrator and educator in [[South Australia]] who helped to raise the status and opportunities for women in sport.

==Contribution to women's sport==
Mills was founding president (1953) of the South Australian Women’s Amateur Sports Council serving as President for seven years. She was President of the Australian Women’s Cricket Council and the S.A. Women’s Cricket Association and became a life member of both.  She helped to establish and develop at St Marys the [http://www.recsport.sa.gov.au/whats-on-where/womens-memorial-pf.html South Australian Women's Memorial Playing Fields], a memorial to women who served in both world wars.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=https://www.womensmemorial.org.au/history|title=History|website=www.womensmemorial.org.au|access-date=2019-01-24}}</ref>

Mills was an avid advocate for women's sport and successfully lobbied then Premier, [[Sir Thomas Playford]], to secure access to playing fields for the dedicated use of women.<ref name=":1">{{Cite web|url=http://www.womenaustralia.info/biogs/AWE2258b.htm|title=Mills, May|last=|first=|date=|website=The Australian Women's Register|language=en-gb|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2019-01-24}}</ref> for the dedication of the entire area of 8 hectares of the Playing Fields in memory of the contribution made by women from the Army, Navy and Air Force during [[World War II]] with a particular focus on the 1942 [[Bangka Island massacre|Bangka Strait massacre]].<ref>{{Cite news|url = http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article972105|title = Massacre of nurses on Banka Beach|last = Rivett|first = Rohan|date = 19 September 1945|work = |access-date = 15 February 2015|newspaper = The Argus|page = 3}}</ref> The Bangka Strait Memorial Service was first held in 1955, with a dedication service in 1956 and has continued annually in February each year.<ref name=":0" />

May helped finance and raise funds for the establishment and maintenance of the Memorial Playing Fields. From 1963 administration of the Playing Fields was taken over by the South Australian Women's Memorial Field Trust and May became President and Life Member. A pavilion there was named after her in 1967.<ref name=":0" />

In 2008 the Minister for Recreation, Sport and Racing, as owner of the land, granted a 21-year lease to the [[South Australian Cricket Association]]. The [[South Australian Cricket Association]] now manages and maintains the fields and has long term plans for the upgrade and development of the facility. Women's cricket, lacrosse, hockey, tennis and soccer all continue to be played at the fields.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://ors.sa.gov.au/our_venues/womens_memorial_playing_fields|title=ORSR - Women's Memorial Playing Fields|website=ors.sa.gov.au|access-date=2019-01-24}}</ref>

The SA Women’s Memorial Playing Fields Trust continues to oversee the Memorial aspect of the site as well as organising the annual Bangka Day Memorial Service.
[[File:J150W-Mills.jpg|alt=Jubilee 150 Walkway plaque — May Mills|thumb|Jubilee 150 Walkway plaque — May Mills]]

==Education and other achievements==
Mills taught at [[Unley High School]] for thirty years. She was the first female President of the South Australian Institute of Teachers in 1943 which eventually became part of the [[Australian Education Union]].<ref name=":1" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.atua.org.au/biogs/ALE1590b.htm#related|title=South Australian Women Teachers Guild|last=|first=|date=|website=ATUA - Australian Trade Union Archives|language=en-gb|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2019-01-24}}</ref> Mills was the first President of the South Australian Film and Television Council, a founding member of the [[Australian College of Educators]], Life Vice-President of the National Council of Women and a Life Member of the [[Royal Commonwealth Society]]. Always a pioneer and innovator she was the first women in South Australia to secure a license to drive a motor car.<ref name=":1" />

==OBE and recognition==
For her services to education and for her work in establishing the Memorial Playing Fields, May was awarded the [[Order of the British Empire]] (OBE) in 1960.<ref name=":2">{{Citation|last=Jones|first=Helen|title=Mills, May (1890–1984)|url=http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/mills-may-14963|work=Australian Dictionary of Biography|publisher=National Centre of Biography, Australian National University|access-date=2019-01-24}}
</ref>

In 1986 a plaque in recognition of her contribution to South Australia was included in the [[Jubilee 150 Walkway]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://adelaidia.sa.gov.au/things/j150-plaque-may-mills|title=J150 Plaque, May Mills|last=|first=|last2=|first2=|date=|website=adelaidia.sa.gov.au|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=2019-01-23}}</ref>

==Death and legacy==
Miss Mills died on 29 January 1984 in Adelaide and was buried in [[Blakiston, South Australia|Blakiston]] cemetery. A bequeath to the [[Flinders University of South Australia]] enabled the establishment of the May Mills re-entry scholarship for women in 1989.<ref name=":2" /> May Mills contribution to women's cricket was recognised in 1984/85 by the creation of the May Mills Trophy for the Under 18 national Championship which ran until 1995/96.<ref name=":1" />

